You are tasked with designing a verilog module that takes in three inputs: a clock signal (`clk`), a data input (`in`), and a reset signal (`reset`). The module should output a signal (`out`) that toggles between 0 and 1 on each rising edge of the clock signal, but only if the input signal (`in`) is different from the previous output signal.

Specifically, the module should behave as follows:
- At the first rising edge of the clock signal, the output signal (`out`) should be 0.
- On each subsequent rising edge of the clock signal, if the input signal (`in`) is different from the previous output signal, the output signal (`out`) should toggle between 0 and 1.
- If the input signal (`in`) is the same as the previous output signal, the output signal (`out`) should remain the same.

If the reset signal (`reset`) is asserted (i.e., goes high), the output signal (`out`) should be set to 0 on the next rising edge of the clock signal, regardless of the input signal (`in`).

You should implement this module using registers and combinational logic.

", "Response": ["module toggle2pulse(
   // Outputs
   out,
   // Inputs
   clk, in, reset
   );

   //clocks
   input  clk; 

   input  in;   
   output out;

   //reset
   input  reset;
   reg 	  out_reg;
   reg   	  out_reg_last;

   always @ (posedge clk) begin
     if(reset) begin
       out_reg <= 1'b0;
     end else begin
       out_reg_last <= out_reg;
       out_reg <= in;
     end
   end

   assign out = (in ^ out_reg_last) ? ~out_reg_last : out_reg_last;

